[[File:Lava Stringer 5.jpg|thumb|right| Lava Stringers on [[Catlow Valley (Oregon)|Catlow Rim]] in [[Oregon]]]]
A '''lava stringer''' is an elongated concentration of mostly [[scree|talus]]-like [[basalt]] rock found along a [[hill]]side or the base of a [[cliff]]. Many stringers occur without cliffs. A stringer is identified by its lack of [[Erosion#Vegetative cover|vegetative cover]]. <ref name="Wildlife Habitats"> {{cite book |author1=Maser, Chris |author2=Geist, J. Michael |author3=Concannon, Diane M. |author4=Anderson, Ralph |author5=Lovell, Burrell |title=Wildlife Habitats in Managed Rangelands-- The Great Basin of Southeastern Oregon: Geomorphic and Edaphic Habitats|publisher=U.S. Department of Agriculture |year=1979 |pages=11–12 |url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uiug.30112104080855;view=1up;seq=13 |accessdate=2016-12-01 }}</ref>
